are mature and liberal.

725
01:06:27,802 --> 01:06:30,639
You think you got a good enough aim...

726
01:06:30,739 --> 01:06:33,141
...for that hammer
to knock these bracelets off me?

727
01:06:33,241 --> 01:06:35,477
Man, I don't want no trouble.

728
01:06:35,577 --> 01:06:38,480
Nothing's gonna happen.
You think you can do it?

729
01:06:38,580 --> 01:06:42,320
I've never missed yet.
- All right, go ahead.

730
01:06:52,527 --> 01:06:54,527
Sorry, man. First time.

731
01:07:00,101 --> 01:07:03,438
Food on a chain gang is scarce
and not very nourishing.

732
01:07:03,538 --> 01:07:07,533
The men get one hot meal a day:
A bowl of steam.

733
01:07:14,282 --> 01:07:18,787
All right, boys,
who didn't give me a good day's work?

734
01:07:26,528 --> 01:07:28,528
Come with us, Wilson.

735
01:07:43,611 --> 01:07:46,581
What's the matter, Starkwell?
Can't you take it?

736
01:07:46,681 --> 01:07:52,546
I want you to see this so you'll know
what you got to look forward to.

737
01:08:06,101 --> 01:08:09,004
Just what in the hell
do you think you're doing?

738
01:08:09,104 --> 01:08:10,538
What do you mean?

739
01:08:10,638 --> 01:08:14,548
Don't beat the shadow, you damn fool.
Beat him.

740
01:08:14,642 --> 01:08:16,642
Him.

741
01:08:17,245 --> 01:08:22,260
The time drags by in an endless grind
of backbreaking labor.

742
01:08:23,451 --> 01:08:26,354
Brutal discipline is common
under the hot sun.

743
01:08:26,454 --> 01:08:30,091
The men are not even permitted to faint
without written permission.

744
01:08:30,191 --> 01:08:33,461
Virgil complains,
and he is severely tortured.

745
01:08:33,561 --> 01:08:37,232
For several days, he is locked
in a sweat box with an insurance salesman.

746
01:08:37,332 --> 01:08:41,703
Hello, I'm Joe Green, and I represent
the Ajax-Witches Insurance company.

747
01:08:41,803 --> 01:08:45,140
I'd like to talk to you about your insurance.
You're about 30, right?

748
01:08:45,240 --> 01:08:49,344
You know, I think the best thing to do is
to get straight life, plus a little term.

749
01:08:49,444 --> 01:08:51,446
And how about dental and medical?

750
01:08:51,546 --> 01:08:55,456
We've got this major medical.
It's a good deal.

751
01:08:57,085 --> 01:09:00,588
At the end of each day, the men are
chained to each other by the ankle...

752
01:09:00,688 --> 01:09:04,292
...in groups of six,
making movement slow and painful...

753
01:09:04,392 --> 01:09:06,517
...and escape impossible.

754
01:09:14,636 --> 01:09:18,291
Then, one day, the impossible is attempted.

755
01:09:24,679 --> 01:09:26,181
See that field?

756
01:09:26,281 --> 01:09:28,650
If we make it across that field,
we'd be out of here.

757
01:09:28,750 --> 01:09:33,088
We can take them by surprise,
if we all suddenly made a break for it.

758
01:09:33,188 --> 01:09:35,423
You're crazy.
- That's right.

759
01:09:35,523 --> 01:09:39,688
I'm a paranoid schizophrenic,
but I say we try it.

760
01:09:39,761 --> 01:09:43,501
Ain't that right, boys?
- Yeah, you're right.

761
01:10:05,119 --> 01:10:07,689
I'm not with them. I wanted to stay.

762
01:10:07,789 --> 01:10:10,509
All right, everybody spread out.

763
01:11:59,667 --> 01:12:01,703
My car broke down. Can I use your phone?

764
01:12:01,803 --> 01:12:03,803
Of course. Come in.

765
01:12:23,291 --> 01:12:25,994
We're gonna get out of here.
I know a guy in town...

766
01:12:26,094 --> 01:12:30,769
...who's got enough tools
to get us out of these chains.

767
01:12:31,399 --> 01:12:36,414
All right. You act natural
and answer it or you're finished.

768
01:12:36,604 --> 01:12:38,006
Who is it?

769
01:12:38,106 --> 01:12:40,741
Patrolman Lynch. Can I come in?

770
01:12:40,842 --> 01:12:42,343
Well, not now.

771
01:12:42,443 --> 01:12:45,013
It's an emergency. I'm afraid I'll have to.

772
01:12:45,113 --> 01:12:46,447
You better untie her.

773
01:12:46,547 --> 01:12:51,052
Tell him we're your cousins
visiting from out of town.

774
01:12:56,491 --> 01:12:59,466
One false move and you're finished.

775
01:13:02,997 --> 01:13:03,998
What is it?

776
01:13:04,098 --> 01:13:06,467
I hear there's been some trouble
up at the prison.

777
01:13:06,567 --> 01:13:09,270
I'm checking the area
for anything suspicious.

778
01:13:09,370 --> 01:13:13,675
These are my cousins.
They're visiting me for the holiday.

779
01:13:13,775 --> 01:13:15,775
What holiday?

780
01:13:16,411 --> 01:13:20,014
Did you ever hear of St. Abernathy's Day?
- No.

781
01:13:20,114 --> 01:13:22,409
That's what we're here for.

782
01:13:22,884 --> 01:13:25,546
Come here, you. Come here.

783
01:13:32,493 --> 01:13:35,463
You think your cousin is safe
living here all alone?

784
01:13:35,563 --> 01:13:37,732
Look how close we are to the prison.

785
01:13:37,832 --> 01:13:42,082
Look out here.
It's just a few miles down the road.

786
01:13:42,103 --> 01:13:44,103
Come here.

787
01:13:47,041 --> 01:13:49,041
I don't know.

788
01:13:49,510 --> 01:13:52,947
You sure can't be sure
when you live so close to a prison.

789
01:13:53,047 --> 01:13:55,047
Wait a minute.

790
01:13:55,049 --> 01:13:57,752
Did I see something move out there?
- You couldn't have.

791
01:13:57,852 --> 01:14:02,724
I'm sure I saw something move. Quick.
Everybody take one window and check it.

792
01:14:02,824 --> 01:14:08,009
If there's somebody out there,
we'll have a chance to see him.

793
01:14:12,200 --> 01:14:15,515
Guess it must have been my imagination.

794
01:14:17,572 --> 01:14:19,572
Now?

795
01:14:20,408 --> 01:14:22,408
Excuse us.

796
01:14:36,758 --> 01:14:38,426
They're escaped convicts.

797
01:14:38,526 --> 01:14:40,461
Really?
- They've broken in.

798
01:14:40,561 --> 01:14:44,065
Didn't you notice how they all
moved together closely?

799
01:14:44,165 --> 01:14:49,704
They're chained together at the ankles.
- I thought they were just a close family.

800
01:14:49,804 --> 01:14:52,272
Okay, boys, the game's up.

801
01:14:55,543 --> 01:14:57,745
The old lady must have told.

802
01:14:57,845 --> 01:15:03,795
You're going back to that prison
and this time you're gonna stay there.

803
01:15:06,454 --> 01:15:07,889
Where we gonna go? We need tools.

804
01:15:07,989 --> 01:15:11,899
Let's get my wife. She'll help us out of this.

805
01:15:18,566 --> 01:15:22,637
Virgil, if you'd only listened to me
and gone straight.

806
01:15:22,737 --> 01:15:26,140
Honey, we needed the money
and I robbed a bank.

807
01:15:26,240 --> 01:15:28,309
When are you going to stop doing that?

808
01:15:28,409 --> 01:15:32,380
Don't you realize you're a father
and you have responsibilities.

809
01:15:32,480 --> 01:15:34,415
If she was my wife, I'd belt her one.

810
01:15:34,515 --> 01:15:36,284
Do you mind keeping out of this, please?

811
01:15:36,384 --> 01:15:39,020
I don't wanna discuss
it, unless we're alone.

812
01:15:39,120 --> 01:15:40,354
I wanna discuss it now.

813
01:15:40,454 --> 01:15:42,990
All right you don't wanna
discuss it alone. Okay.

814
01:15:43,090 --> 01:15:44,058
Where are you going?

815
01:15:44,158 --> 01:15:46,527
I'm going to the next room,
to talk about it right now.

816
01:15:46,627 --> 01:15:49,063
I can't come in alone. I'm chained to the...

817
01:15:49,163 --> 01:15:53,000
We can't be alone unless we go someplace
where they got some tools or something.

818
01:15:53,100 --> 01:15:55,136
These guys are with me for good now.

819
01:15:55,236 --> 01:15:56,504
How do you think I feel?

820
01:15:56,604 --> 01:16:00,854
I'm a young woman,
sleeping alone here every night.

821
01:16:01,309 --> 01:16:02,310
Darling, look...

822
01:16:02,410 --> 01:16:05,113
Don't you think
that means something to me?

823
01:16:05,213 --> 01:16:07,949
I think back to the days
when you were in the Philharmonic.

824
01:16:08,049 --> 01:16:10,084
I was never in the Philharmonic.

825
01:16:10,184 --> 01:16:12,954
We used to lie in bed
and you used to make love to me.

826
01:16:13,054 --> 01:16:15,857
And you used to recite poetry...
- Poetry?

827
01:16:15,957 --> 01:16:20,462
And play with that doll you got me.
- Hey, Longfellow.

828
01:16:20,895 --> 01:16:22,630
Darling, look.

829
01:16:22,730 --> 01:16:24,532
You guys look away for a minute.

830
01:16:24,632 --> 01:16:26,868
Sweetheart, don't you know
that whatever happens...

831
01:16:26,968 --> 01:16:29,937
...you're always gonna
mean the same to me.

832
01:16:30,037 --> 01:16:32,037
Will you stop giggling?

833
01:16:32,740 --> 01:16:36,577
You'll always mean the sun,
and earth and the moon to me.

834
01:16:36,677 --> 01:16:38,677
Oh, Christ.

835
01:16:41,315 --> 01:16:44,852
With Louise's help,
the chains are removed from Virgil's ankles.

836
01:16:44,952 --> 01:16:47,188
Once more the family takes flight...

837
01:16:47,288 --> 01:16:53,408
...feeling guilty about their son's education.
Louise tries tutoring him.

838
01:16:57,064 --> 01:16:59,189
He's been very depressed.

839
01:17:02,336 --> 01:17:05,339
I think if he had been
a successful criminal...

840
01:17:05,439 --> 01:17:07,734
...he would've felt better.

841
01:17:08,109 --> 01:17:12,213
You know, he never made
the 'Ten Most Wanted' list.

842
01:17:12,313 --> 01:17:15,483
It's very unfair voting. It's who you know.

843
01:17:15,583 --> 01:17:18,219
Virgil Starkwell embarks on
a series of crimes...

844
01:17:18,319 --> 01:17:21,379
...that make him a wanted desperado.

845
01:17:33,401 --> 01:17:35,536
Here, he attempts to rob
the vault of a bank...

846
01:17:35,636 --> 01:17:39,801
...but finds a family of Gypsies
are living there.

847
01:17:41,509 --> 01:17:46,447
By the end of six months,
the FBI regards Virgil as a menace.

848
01:17:46,547 --> 01:17:49,016
Although he does not make
the 'Ten Most Wanted' list...

849
01:17:49,116 --> 01:17:51,519
...he does win 'Gangster
of the Year' award...

850
01:17:51,619 --> 01:17:55,857
...and is asked to speak
at many luncheons and universities.

851
01:17:55,957 --> 01:17:58,726
For the end of this story,
we spoke to Mr. Daniel Miller...

852
01:17:58,826 --> 01:18:02,530
...an FBI agent and author of the book,
Mother Was A Red.

853
01:18:02,630 --> 01:18:05,967
The FBI actually wanted Virgil very badly.

854
01:18:06,067 --> 01:18:10,371
Mr. Hoover was quite upset
by Mr. Starkwell and his activities.

855
01:18:10,471 --> 01:18:14,275
In fact, he confided to me
on several occasions.

856
01:18:14,375 --> 01:18:19,046
I can remember one very well,
after a bowling match on Thursday night...

857
01:18:19,146 --> 01:18:21,518
...on which he said he
couldn't sleep nights,

858
01:18:21,618 --> 01:18:23,451
he was smoking a little too much...

859
01:18:23,551 --> 01:18:27,954
...and he thought that this criminal...

860
01:18:28,189 --> 01:18:33,374
...as he put it, might very well be
part of a subversive plot.

861
01:18:34,795 --> 01:18:39,562
Obviously an atheist and a pinko...

862
01:18:40,201 --> 01:18:44,281
...and trying in general
to disturb our society.

863
01:18:45,139 --> 01:18:47,842
We finally traced him
to a cheap neighborhood...

864
01:18:47,942 --> 01:18:50,478
...down on the Lower
East Side of New York...

865
01:18:50,578 --> 01:18:55,016
...where he was living, at the time,
in a very sleazy, rundown tenement house.

866
01:18:55,116 --> 01:18:58,753
Virge? I remember him.
I used to live with him as a matter of fact.

867
01:18:58,853 --> 01:19:01,422
In the same rooming house, that is.

868
01:19:01,522 --> 01:19:04,225
One day, he told me he was a gynecologist.

869
01:19:04,325 --> 01:19:09,255
He couldn't speak no foreign languages.
Who was he kidding?

870
01:19:09,530 --> 01:19:13,401
I thought I saw his picture on a post office...

871
01:19:13,501 --> 01:19:17,772
I didn't remember whether it was
on the wall or on a stamp.

872
01:19:17,872 --> 01:19:20,422
Do you remember Virgil?
- Yeah.

873
01:19:20,441 --> 01:19:23,945
What was he like?
- I don't know. Now, I think he was brilliant.

874
01:19:24,045 --> 01:19:25,379
Just absolutely brilliant.

875
01:19:25,479 --> 01:19:29,216
When I found out that he was a criminal,
I just couldn't believe lt.

876
01:19:29,316 --> 01:19:32,911
I just thought I was gonna die...

877
01:19:32,987 --> 01:19:36,157
'cause he just was the best cover-up job
I've ever seen in my life.

878
01:19:36,257 --> 01:19:37,959
I mean, unbelievable acting job.

879
01:19:38,059 --> 01:19:41,896
I actually believed that he was an idiot.
I really believed it.

880
01:19:41,996 --> 01:19:44,732
And I wasn't the only one.
Everybody thought so.

881
01:19:44,832 --> 01:19:48,035
Everyone thought he was a schlemiel,
and turns out he's a criminal.

882
01:19:48,135 --> 01:19:51,639
Just to think that that idiot was a criminal.
I just can't believe it.

883
01:19:51,739 --> 01:19:54,342
I mean, you never met anybody like this
in your life.

884
01:19:54,442 --> 01:19:56,243
You've never met such a nothing.

885
01:19:56,343 --> 01:19:59,213
I can't believe it.
That there was a mind working in there...

886
01:19:59,313 --> 01:20:02,416
...that could rob banks. It's phenomenal.

887
01:20:02,516 --> 01:20:06,020
Do you know that once I said to him,
'What do you do?'

888
01:20:06,120 --> 01:20:08,452
He said, 'I rob banks.'

889
01:20:08,522 --> 01:20:10,522
Go know?

890
01:20:11,158 --> 01:20:12,893
But we finally caught up to him.

891
01:20:12,993 --> 01:20:16,731
I think it was April 11th.
We finally captured Virgil...

892
01:20:16,831 --> 01:20:20,231
...under sort of very odd circumstances.

893
01:20:20,634 --> 01:20:23,904
An amateur photographer
happened to be there at the time...

894
01:20:24,004 --> 01:20:27,999
...and took the only known films
of his capture.

895
01:20:28,576 --> 01:20:31,779
I was coming down here.
This is the spot where it actually happened.

896
01:20:31,879 --> 01:20:32,913
You see.

897
01:20:33,013 --> 01:20:36,317
As a matter of fact, I had just
brought my pants in to the cleaners...

898
01:20:36,417 --> 01:20:38,152
...and I was sort of angry with them...

899
01:20:38,252 --> 01:20:41,889
...because last time I asked them
to sew a button on and they hadn't.

900
01:20:41,989 --> 01:20:44,199
Will you get to the point?

901
01:20:44,225 --> 01:20:46,225
Oh, yes. Well...

902
01:20:47,695 --> 01:20:51,599
I'll tell you exactly what happened
this morning with me.

903
01:20:51,699 --> 01:20:56,537
And about the camera. Well, back to
this thing in which I became known...

904
01:20:56,637 --> 01:20:59,106
...merely because of what happened
and I had the camera.

905
01:20:59,206 --> 01:21:01,342
I was having breakfast in the morning.

906
01:21:01,442 --> 01:21:04,757
I think it was two fried eggs, toast...

907
01:21:05,646 --> 01:21:10,451
...and juice, I don't know whether it was
orange or grapefruit.

908
01:21:10,551 --> 01:21:13,454
But at that time...
It was orange juice, that's right.

909
01:21:13,554 --> 01:21:14,955
Will you get to the point?

910
01:21:15,055 --> 01:21:17,792
I've got them right here.
I'd like to show them to you.

911
01:21:17,892 --> 01:21:19,393
The very last films...

912
01:21:19,493 --> 01:21:23,573
...of Virgil Starkwell
being captured by the FBI.

913
01:21:24,064 --> 01:21:26,667
All right, get your hands up.
This is a stickup.

914
01:21:26,767 --> 01:21:30,422
I know you. Virgil Starkwell, that's right.

915
01:21:32,706 --> 01:21:35,681
Eddie? What? Haynes?
- That's right.

916
01:21:35,809 --> 01:21:38,612
We were in the marching band together,
and you played a cello.

917
01:21:38,712 --> 01:21:40,848
I was trombone. First trombone.

918
01:21:40,948 --> 01:21:43,382
Isn't that funny? My God.

919
01:21:43,450 --> 01:21:46,353
What are you doing?
- I'm with the Philharmonic.

920
01:21:46,453 --> 01:21:49,123
No kidding. That's great.
I was just talking to someone...

921
01:21:49,223 --> 01:21:52,526
Oscar Sunkin. About the great times
we used to have together, remember?

922
01:21:52,626 --> 01:21:54,028
They were hilarious.

923
01:21:54,128 --> 01:21:56,363
Do you do you remember
when we got caught...

924
01:21:56,463 --> 01:21:58,299
...taking a shower in the girls' locker room?

925
01:21:58,399 --> 01:22:01,001
I do. You know,
I never saw anybody so embarrassed.

926
01:22:01,101 --> 01:22:02,236
I'll never forget your face.

927
01:22:02,336 --> 01:22:04,071
My face. You dropped the towel.

928
01:22:04,171 --> 01:22:07,072
You dropped the towel, too.

929
01:22:07,141 --> 01:22:08,976
Let me have your watch, will you?

930
01:22:09,076 --> 01:22:11,076
Yes, sure.

931
01:22:11,612 --> 01:22:15,548
Remember that... We
painted the car yellow.

932
01:22:15,616 --> 01:22:18,052
Right, on Halloween.
- That's right. It was Halloween.

933
01:22:18,152 --> 01:22:20,554
It was really funny.
- It was yellow stripes.

934
01:22:20,654 --> 01:22:22,723
That's right, like a barber pole.

935
01:22:22,823 --> 01:22:24,859
Keep your hands up
or I'll have to shoot you.

936
01:22:24,959 --> 01:22:26,193
Yeah, sure.

937
01:22:26,293 --> 01:22:29,196
Jesus, remember the football game?
- You fumbled the last play.

938
01:22:29,296 --> 01:22:31,332
And you picked up the ball and ran with it.

939
01:22:31,432 --> 01:22:34,368
And then I ran the wrong way.
Everybody was yelling, 'Go back.'

940
01:22:34,468 --> 01:22:36,003
And I thought they were cheering.

941
01:22:36,103 --> 01:22:37,872
You can't beat the good old days.

942
01:22:37,972 --> 01:22:41,876
No, or the good old nights.
Shirley Sistrin. Remember?

943
01:22:41,976 --> 01:22:43,277
The wallet.

944
01:22:43,377 --> 01:22:45,607
I didn't hear you.

945
01:22:46,046 --> 01:22:48,682
It's been great speaking to you, really.

946
01:22:48,782 --> 01:22:51,585
It's so nice to see you.
- Yeah, you, too. Take it easy.

947
01:22:51,685 --> 01:22:54,989
Maybe I'll see you again.
- Best of luck to you.

948
01:22:55,089 --> 01:22:57,724
I just realized that I'm a cop.

949
01:22:57,958 --> 01:23:00,494
No kidding. How's it going?
- It's a great job.

950
01:23:00,594 --> 01:23:04,928
I get a pension.
- Do you remember when we...

951
01:23:05,532 --> 01:23:08,936
Virgil Starkwell is tried on
52 counts of robbery...

952
01:23:09,036 --> 01:23:12,673
...and is sentenced to
800 years in federal prison.

953
01:23:12,773 --> 01:23:15,476
At the trial, he tells his lawyer confidently...

954
01:23:15,576 --> 01:23:18,879
...that with good behavior,
he can cut the sentence in half.

955
01:23:18,979 --> 01:23:22,850
Now that you're caught and you're facing
a very long prison sentence...

956
01:23:22,950 --> 01:23:25,920
...do you have any regrets
about choosing a life of crime?

957
01:23:26,020 --> 01:23:28,289
